\begin{enumerate}

\item Use a scaling argument to show that maximal rowing speed $V$ increases as the number of oarsmen $N$ as $V ~\alpha ~ N ^{1/9} $.

\bigskip
\underline{Solution:} First we can assume that the number of oarsmen is proportional to the total power output and that the power is proportional to the drag force times velocity:
\begin{equation} N ~ \alpha ~ P ~\alpha ~ D_f V .\end{equation}
We'll assume that the drag force is from friction, and so we can write 
\begin{equation} D_f ~\alpha ~ V ^2 A_w \end{equation}
where $A_w$ is the wetted surface of the vessel.
Now we go for $A_w$, which we assume is proportional to $l^2$, the length of the vessel squared, due to the isometry of the situation.
This is
\begin{equation} A_w ~\alpha ~ l^2 .\end{equation}
Of course the volume of displacement of water is proportional to the number of oarsmen, and the volume is proportional to $l^3$ since the shape of the boat is growing isometrically and we assume the displacement grows isometrically with the length of the vessel.
This is:
\begin{equation} N ~\alpha ~ V_d ~ \alpha ~ \left ( d \cdot l \cdot w\right )  ~\alpha ~ l^3 ~~~\Rightarrow ~~~ l ~\alpha ~N ^{1/3} .\end{equation}
Now we do some substitution.
Plugging (4) into (3) we have
\begin{equation} A_w ~ \alpha ~ N ^{2/3} . \end{equation}
Plugging this, (5), into (2) we have
\begin{equation} D_f ~\alpha ~ V^2 N ^{2/3} .\end{equation}
Finally, we plug (6) into (1) and solve:
\[ N ~\alpha ~ (V^2  N ^{1/3} ) V = V^3 N^{2/3} ~~~\Rightarrow ~~~ N^{1/3} ~\alpha ~ V ^3 ~~~\Rightarrow ~~~ N ^{1/9} ~\alpha ~ V .\]


